<!--
========================================================================
FILE: Checkout.view.xml — Checkout / Order Placement Page
NAMESPACE: com.shopeasy.app.view
========================================================================

[BEGINNER] WHAT IS THIS VIEW?
The checkout page guides users through placing an order. It uses the
sap.m.Wizard control to create a multi-step form with:
  Step 1: Shipping Address (form with input fields)
  Step 2: Payment Method (radio button selection)
  Step 3: Order Summary (cart items + total)

[INTERMEDIATE] KEY CONCEPTS DEMONSTRATED:
  - sap.m.Wizard for multi-step workflows
  - sap.ui.layout.form.SimpleForm for form layouts
  - Input controls with validation (Input, Select, RadioButtonGroup)
  - MessageStrip for inline feedback
  - Binding across multiple models (cart + i18n + local form data)
  - Form patterns and best practices in UI5

[ADVANCED] FORM HANDLING IN UI5
UI5 does NOT have built-in "form state management" like React Hook Form
or Angular Reactive Forms. Instead:
  - Bind input controls to a local JSONModel
  - Validate in the controller using Input's valueState property
  - Show errors via MessageStrip, MessageBox, or MessageToast
  - Submit by reading the model data and sending it to the backend

Learn more: docs/06-controls.md, docs/09-formatting.md
========================================================================
-->

<mvc:View
    controllerName="com.shopeasy.app.controller.Checkout"
    xmlns="sap.m"
    xmlns:mvc="sap.ui.core.mvc"
    xmlns:core="sap.ui.core"
    xmlns:l="sap.ui.layout"
    xmlns:form="sap.ui.layout.form"
>
    <!--
    [BEGINNER] NAMESPACE FOR FORM CONTROLS
    ====================================================
    xmlns:form="sap.ui.layout.form"
      This namespace gives us access to form layout controls:
        - form:SimpleForm → A simplified form layout
        - form:Form → A more powerful form layout with FormContainers
        - form:FormElement → Individual form field wrapper

    xmlns:l="sap.ui.layout"
      This namespace gives us access to layout controls:
        - l:Grid → CSS Grid layout
        - l:VerticalLayout / l:HorizontalLayout → Simple layouts
        - l:ResponsiveFlowLayout → Flow layout that wraps

    [INTERMEDIATE] WHY SEPARATE NAMESPACES?
    UI5 organizes controls into libraries by function:
      sap.m        → Mobile/responsive controls (buttons, lists, pages)
      sap.ui.core  → Core framework controls (Icon, Item)
      sap.ui.layout → Layout controls (Grid, Splitter)
      sap.ui.layout.form → Form-specific layout controls
      sap.f        → Fiori-specific controls (Avatar, GridList)

    Each library is loaded independently, so you only load what you need.
    -->

    <Page
        id="checkoutPage"
        title="{i18n>checkoutTitle}"
        showNavButton="true"
        navButtonPress=".onNavBack"
    >

        <!--
        [INTERMEDIATE] THE <MessageStrip> CONTROL — Inline Notifications
        ====================================================
        sap.m.MessageStrip displays a colored bar with a message.
        It's used for inline notifications, warnings, or errors
        within a page (as opposed to MessageBox which is a modal dialog).

        type="Information"
          [BEGINNER] MessageStrip types and their colors:
            - "Information" → Blue bar with info icon
            - "Success"     → Green bar with checkmark icon
            - "Warning"     → Orange bar with warning icon
            - "Error"       → Red bar with error icon

        showCloseButton="true"
          Shows an "X" to dismiss the message. Once closed, the
          MessageStrip is hidden but not destroyed — the controller
          can show it again.

        visible="{checkout>/messageStripVisible}"
          [INTERMEDIATE] Bound to a local view model. The controller
          sets this to true when validation fails, showing the error
          message. After the user corrects the input, it can be hidden.

        text="{checkout>/messageStripText}"
          The message text, also from the local view model. This lets
          the controller dynamically change the message based on which
          validation failed.

        [BEST PRACTICE] VALIDATION FEEDBACK HIERARCHY
        UI5 offers several ways to show validation feedback:
          1. Input's valueState      → Per-field error (red border)
          2. Input's valueStateText  → Per-field error message
          3. MessageStrip            → Section-level or form-level message
          4. MessageToast            → Transient notification (disappears)
          5. MessageBox              → Modal confirmation/error dialog
          6. Message Manager         → Collects all messages in a list

        Use them in combination:
          - valueState on each invalid input (shows which fields are wrong)
          - MessageStrip at the top of the form (summary: "Please fill required fields")
          - MessageToast for success ("Order placed!")
        -->
        <MessageStrip
            text="{checkout>/messageStripText}"
            type="{checkout>/messageStripType}"
            showCloseButton="true"
            visible="{checkout>/messageStripVisible}"
            class="sapUiSmallMargin"
        />

        <!--
        [BEGINNER] THE <Wizard> CONTROL — Multi-Step Workflow
        ====================================================
        sap.m.Wizard creates a step-by-step guided workflow. Each step
        has a title, an optional icon, and content. The user progresses
        through steps sequentially.

        Think of it like a multi-page form:
          Step 1: Shipping → Step 2: Payment → Step 3: Review → Done!

        id="checkoutWizard"
          Used by the controller to manage step navigation:
            var oWizard = this.byId("checkoutWizard");
            oWizard.nextStep();      // Go to next step
            oWizard.previousStep();  // Go back
            oWizard.goToStep(oStep); // Jump to specific step

        complete=".onWizardComplete"
          [INTERMEDIATE] Fires when the user reaches the LAST step and
          clicks the "complete" action. This is where you'd submit
          the order to the backend.

        [INTERMEDIATE] HOW THE WIZARD WORKS
          - Steps are shown sequentially (step 1, then 2, then 3)
          - Each step has a "validated" property that gates progression
          - When validated="true", the "Next Step" button appears
          - All completed steps remain visible (scrolled up) so the
            user can review/edit previous entries
          - The step indicators at the top show progress

        [ADVANCED] WIZARD vs. MANUAL STEP MANAGEMENT
        You could build a step-by-step form manually using:
          - IconTabBar with tabs for each step
          - NavContainer with pages for each step
          - Conditional visibility on VBox containers

        But the Wizard control provides:
          - Built-in step indicators (numbered circles)
          - Automatic "Next Step" button management
          - Step validation gating (can't skip ahead)
          - Responsive layout on different screen sizes
          - Fiori-compliant design out of the box
        -->
        <Wizard
            id="checkoutWizard"
            complete=".onWizardComplete"
            class="sapUiResponsiveContentPadding"
        >
            <!--
            ============================================================
            STEP 1: SHIPPING ADDRESS
            ============================================================

            [BEGINNER] THE <WizardStep> CONTROL
            ====================================================
            Each WizardStep represents one phase of the workflow.

            id="shippingStep"
              Used by the controller to reference this step:
                var oStep = this.byId("shippingStep");
                oWizard.validateStep(oStep); // Mark as complete

            title="{i18n>shippingAddress}"
              The step title shown in the step indicator and as a heading.

            icon="sap-icon://shipping-status"
              Icon shown in the step indicator circle (before completion).

            validated="false"
              [INTERMEDIATE] STEP VALIDATION
              When false, the "Next Step" button is NOT shown. The user
              cannot proceed until the controller sets validated to true
              (after form validation passes).

              In the controller:
                // After validating all shipping fields:
                this.byId("checkoutWizard").validateStep(
                  this.byId("shippingStep")
                );
            -->
            <WizardStep
                id="shippingStep"
                title="{i18n>shippingAddress}"
                icon="sap-icon://shipping-status"
                validated="false"
                activate=".onShippingStepActivate"
            >
                <!--
                [BEGINNER] THE <form:SimpleForm> CONTROL
                ====================================================
                sap.ui.layout.form.SimpleForm is the EASIEST way to
                create forms in UI5. You just list Labels and Inputs
                alternately, and SimpleForm handles the layout.

                It automatically:
                  - Pairs each Label with the next Input control
                  - Arranges them in columns based on screen size
                  - Handles responsive layout (1 column on phone,
                    2 columns on tablet, 3 on desktop)
                  - Applies proper spacing and alignment

                editable="true"
                  [BEGINNER] When true, the form is in "edit mode"
                  (inputs are editable). When false, inputs display
                  as read-only text. This toggle is useful for
                  view/edit mode switching.

                layout="ResponsiveGridLayout"
                  [INTERMEDIATE] SimpleForm supports multiple layouts:
                    - "ResponsiveGridLayout": CSS Grid-based, most flexible
                    - "ResponsiveLayout": Flexbox-based, simpler
                    - "GridLayout": Fixed grid, less responsive
                    - "ColumnLayout": Column-based, newest option

                  [BEST PRACTICE] Use ResponsiveGridLayout for forms.
                  It provides the best responsive behavior and is
                  recommended by SAP Fiori design guidelines.

                columnsL="2" columnsM="1"
                  [INTERMEDIATE] How many columns on each screen size:
                    - columnsL="2": Large screens → 2-column form
                    - columnsM="1": Medium screens → 1-column form
                  On small (phone) screens, it's always 1 column.

                [ADVANCED] SimpleForm vs. Form
                SimpleForm is a convenience wrapper. For complex forms
                with groups, custom layouts, or dynamic form fields,
                use the full sap.ui.layout.form.Form control with
                FormContainers and FormElements. SimpleForm uses
                Labels as group/field delimiters, which limits flexibility.

                [INTERMEDIATE] FORM FIELDS STRUCTURE
                In SimpleForm, the pattern is:
                  <Label text="Field Name" />
                  <Input value="{model>/path}" />

                Each Label is automatically associated with the next
                control. This association:
                  1. Shows the label text next to the input
                  2. Clicking the label focuses the input (accessibility)
                  3. Screen readers announce the label when the input
                     is focused
                -->
                <form:SimpleForm
                    id="shippingForm"
                    editable="true"
                    layout="ResponsiveGridLayout"
                    columnsL="2"
                    columnsM="1"
                    title="{i18n>shippingAddress}"
                >
                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] <Label> AND <Input> PAIRS
                    ====================================================
                    Each Label + Input pair represents one form field.

                    Label properties:
                      text:     The field label text (from i18n)
                      required: Shows a red asterisk (*) indicating
                                the field is mandatory

                    Input properties:
                      value:         Bound to a local form model
                      placeholder:   Ghost text when empty
                      valueState:    Visual state (None, Error, Warning, Success)
                      valueStateText: Message shown with Error/Warning state
                      liveChange:    Event fired on every keystroke
                      required:      HTML5 required attribute

                    [INTERMEDIATE] INPUT VALIDATION PATTERN
                    UI5 inputs don't validate automatically. The pattern is:
                      1. User types in the input
                      2. Controller's liveChange handler validates the value
                      3. If invalid, set valueState="Error" and valueStateText
                      4. If valid, set valueState="None"
                      5. Before proceeding, check all fields' valueState

                    [BEST PRACTICE] BINDING FORM DATA TO A LOCAL MODEL
                    Create a separate JSONModel for form data:
                      var oFormModel = new JSONModel({
                        firstName: "", lastName: "", email: "",
                        phone: "", address: "", city: "",
                        zipCode: "", country: ""
                      });
                      this.getView().setModel(oFormModel, "shipping");

                    This keeps form data separate from business data
                    and makes it easy to reset or submit the entire form.
                    -->

                    <!-- First Name -->
                    <Label
                        text="{i18n>firstName}"
                        required="true"
                    />
                    <Input
                        id="firstNameInput"
                        value="{checkout>/firstName}"
                        placeholder="{i18n>firstName}"
                        liveChange=".onFormFieldChange"
                        required="true"
                    />

                    <!-- Last Name -->
                    <Label
                        text="{i18n>lastName}"
                        required="true"
                    />
                    <Input
                        id="lastNameInput"
                        value="{checkout>/lastName}"
                        placeholder="{i18n>lastName}"
                        liveChange=".onFormFieldChange"
                        required="true"
                    />

                    <!--
                    [INTERMEDIATE] EMAIL INPUT WITH TYPE
                    ====================================================
                    type="Email"
                      sap.m.Input supports multiple input types that
                      control the on-screen keyboard on mobile devices:
                        - "Text"     → Default keyboard
                        - "Email"    → Keyboard with @ and .com keys
                        - "Number"   → Numeric keypad
                        - "Tel"      → Phone number keypad
                        - "Url"      → Keyboard with / and .com keys
                        - "Password" → Masked input

                      [GOTCHA] The type property controls the KEYBOARD,
                      not validation! type="Email" shows an email
                      keyboard but does NOT validate email format.
                      You must validate in the controller.

                    [ADVANCED] INPUT VALIDATION WITH UI5 TYPES
                    For automatic validation, use the "type" binding
                    option (different from the Input's type property!):
                      value="{
                        path: 'checkout>/email',
                        type: 'sap.ui.model.type.String',
                        constraints: { minLength: 5 }
                      }"
                    This creates a binding type that validates the
                    value and shows errors automatically. For email
                    validation, you'd create a custom type.
                    -->
                    <Label
                        text="{i18n>email}"
                        required="true"
                    />
                    <Input
                        id="emailInput"
                        value="{checkout>/email}"
                        placeholder="{i18n>email}"
                        type="Email"
                        liveChange=".onFormFieldChange"
                        required="true"
                    />

                    <!-- Phone -->
                    <Label text="{i18n>phone}" />
                    <Input
                        id="phoneInput"
                        value="{checkout>/phone}"
                        placeholder="{i18n>phone}"
                        type="Tel"
                        liveChange=".onFormFieldChange"
                    />

                    <!-- Address -->
                    <Label
                        text="{i18n>address}"
                        required="true"
                    />
                    <Input
                        id="addressInput"
                        value="{checkout>/address}"
                        placeholder="{i18n>address}"
                        liveChange=".onFormFieldChange"
                        required="true"
                    />

                    <!-- City -->
                    <Label
                        text="{i18n>city}"
                        required="true"
                    />
                    <Input
                        id="cityInput"
                        value="{checkout>/city}"
                        placeholder="{i18n>city}"
                        liveChange=".onFormFieldChange"
                        required="true"
                    />

                    <!-- ZIP Code -->
                    <Label
                        text="{i18n>zipCode}"
                        required="true"
                    />
                    <Input
                        id="zipCodeInput"
                        value="{checkout>/zipCode}"
                        placeholder="{i18n>zipCode}"
                        liveChange=".onFormFieldChange"
                        required="true"
                    />

                    <!--
                    [INTERMEDIATE] COUNTRY SELECTION WITH <Select>
                    ====================================================
                    For predefined options like countries, a Select
                    (dropdown) is better than a free-text Input:
                      - Prevents typos (user picks from a list)
                      - Ensures valid values (standardized country codes)
                      - Better UX on mobile (native picker)

                    change=".onCountryChange"
                      Fires when the user picks a different country.
                      The controller can use this to update shipping
                      costs, available payment methods, etc.

                    selectedKey="{checkout>/country}"
                      [INTERMEDIATE] TWO-WAY BINDING ON SELECTED KEY
                      The selected value is automatically stored in the
                      shipping model at path /country. When the model
                      changes, the Select updates; when the user picks
                      a new option, the model updates. This is two-way
                      binding in action.

                    [ADVANCED] For a complete country list, you'd bind
                    the items to a JSON file or a backend service:
                      items="{countries>/list}"
                    with <core:Item key="{countries>code}" text="{countries>name}" />
                    -->
                    <Label
                        text="{i18n>country}"
                        required="true"
                    />
                    <Select
                        id="countrySelect"
                        selectedKey="{checkout>/country}"
                        change=".onFormFieldChange"
                    >
                        <core:Item key="US" text="United States" />
                        <core:Item key="DE" text="Germany" />
                        <core:Item key="GB" text="United Kingdom" />
                        <core:Item key="FR" text="France" />
                        <core:Item key="JP" text="Japan" />
                        <core:Item key="CN" text="China" />
                        <core:Item key="IN" text="India" />
                        <core:Item key="BR" text="Brazil" />
                    </Select>
                </form:SimpleForm>
            </WizardStep>

            <!--
            ============================================================
            STEP 2: PAYMENT METHOD
            ============================================================

            [BEGINNER] PAYMENT STEP
            The second wizard step lets users choose a payment method.
            We use RadioButtonGroup for single-selection from a small
            set of options.
            -->
            <WizardStep
                id="paymentStep"
                title="{i18n>paymentMethod}"
                icon="sap-icon://credit-card"
                activate=".onPaymentStepActivate"
            >
                <VBox class="sapUiMediumMargin">
                    <Title
                        text="{i18n>paymentMethod}"
                        level="H3"
                        class="sapUiSmallMarginBottom"
                    />

                    <!--
                    [INTERMEDIATE] THE <RadioButtonGroup> CONTROL
                    ====================================================
                    sap.m.RadioButtonGroup manages a set of radio buttons
                    where only ONE can be selected at a time.

                    columns="1"
                      Arranges radio buttons in a single column (stacked).
                      Set to 2 or 3 for a multi-column layout.

                    selectedIndex="0"
                      [BEGINNER] The initially selected radio button
                      (0-based index). Index 0 = first option.

                    select=".onPaymentMethodSelect"
                      Fires when the user picks a different payment method.

                    [BEGINNER] RADIO BUTTONS vs. CHECKBOX vs. SELECT
                      - RadioButtonGroup: Pick ONE from a SMALL set (2-5)
                      - CheckBox: Toggle ON/OFF for each option independently
                      - Select (dropdown): Pick ONE from a LARGER set (5+)
                      - MultiComboBox: Pick MULTIPLE from a large set

                    [BEST PRACTICE] Use radio buttons when:
                      - There are 2-5 options
                      - All options should be visible at once
                      - The user needs to compare options

                    Use a Select (dropdown) when:
                      - There are more than 5 options
                      - Screen space is limited
                      - Options don't need comparison
                    -->
                    <RadioButtonGroup
                        id="paymentMethodGroup"
                        columns="1"
                        selectedIndex="0"
                        select=".onPaymentMethodSelect"
                        class="sapUiSmallMarginBottom"
                    >
                        <!--
                        [BEGINNER] <RadioButton> — Single Option
                        Each RadioButton has a text label. The group
                        ensures only one can be selected.

                        [INTERMEDIATE] For more complex radio options
                        (e.g., showing logos, descriptions), you'd use
                        CustomListItem with a List in "SingleSelectMaster"
                        mode instead of RadioButtonGroup.
                        -->
                        <RadioButton text="Credit Card" />
                        <RadioButton text="PayPal" />
                        <RadioButton text="Bank Transfer" />
                        <RadioButton text="Cash on Delivery" />
                    </RadioButtonGroup>

                    <!--
                    [INTERMEDIATE] PAYMENT DETAILS PLACEHOLDER
                    In a real app, selecting a payment method would
                    show additional form fields:
                      - Credit Card: Card number, expiry, CVV
                      - PayPal: Redirect to PayPal login
                      - Bank Transfer: Bank account details

                    These would be implemented with conditional visibility
                    based on the selected radio button index.
                    -->
                    <MessageStrip
                        text="Payment details would be collected here based on the selected method."
                        type="Information"
                        showIcon="true"
                    />
                </VBox>
            </WizardStep>

            <!--
            ============================================================
            STEP 3: ORDER SUMMARY
            ============================================================

            [BEGINNER] ORDER SUMMARY STEP
            The final step shows a summary of the order before the user
            confirms. It displays:
              - Cart items (from cart model)
              - Total price
              - "Place Order" button

            [BEST PRACTICE] ORDER REVIEW BEFORE SUBMISSION
            Always show users a summary before they commit to an action
            (especially payments). This reduces errors and builds trust.
            The summary should include ALL relevant info:
              - What they're buying (items, quantities)
              - How much it costs (itemized + total)
              - Where it's shipping (address from step 1)
              - How they're paying (method from step 2)
            -->
            <WizardStep
                id="summaryStep"
                title="{i18n>orderSummary}"
                icon="sap-icon://bar-chart"
                activate=".onSummaryStepActivate"
            >
                <VBox class="sapUiMediumMargin">
                    <Title
                        text="{i18n>orderSummary}"
                        level="H3"
                        class="sapUiSmallMarginBottom"
                    />

                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] ORDER ITEMS LIST
                    ====================================================
                    A simple List bound to the cart items. Each item
                    shows as a StandardListItem with the product name,
                    price, and quantity.

                    items="{cart>/items}"
                      Aggregation binding to the cart model's items array.

                    [INTERMEDIATE] StandardListItem vs. ObjectListItem
                    We use StandardListItem here because we need a simpler
                    display than the full ObjectListItem:
                      - title: Product name
                      - description: Quantity info
                      - info: Price
                      - infoState: Color for the price (neutral)
                    -->
                    <List
                        id="summaryList"
                        items="{cart>/items}"
                        headerText="{i18n>cartTitle}"
                    >
                        <StandardListItem
                            title="{cart>name}"
                            description="{= 'Qty: ' + ${cart>quantity}}"
                            info="{
                                path: 'cart>price',
                                formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
                            }"
                            infoState="None"
                            icon="{cart>imageUrl}"
                        />
                    </List>

                    <!--
                    [INTERMEDIATE] ORDER TOTAL SECTION
                    ====================================================
                    A visually distinct section showing the total cost.
                    We use an HBox to lay out the label and amount
                    side by side.

                    [ADVANCED] PANEL CONTROL FOR SECTIONS
                    An alternative approach would be to wrap the total
                    in a Panel control for a card-like appearance:
                      <Panel headerText="Order Total" expandable="false">
                        <ObjectNumber ... />
                      </Panel>
                    -->
                    <HBox
                        alignItems="Center"
                        justifyContent="End"
                        class="sapUiMediumMarginTop"
                    >
                        <Title
                            text="{i18n>total}:"
                            level="H3"
                            class="sapUiSmallMarginEnd"
                        />
                        <ObjectNumber
                            number="{
                                path: 'cart>/totalPrice',
                                formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
                            }"
                            unit="{cart>/currency}"
                            emphasized="true"
                        />
                    </HBox>

                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] PLACE ORDER BUTTON
                    ====================================================
                    The final action button. Pressing this submits the
                    order (in a real app, this would call an OData
                    create operation or a custom backend API).

                    press=".onPlaceOrder"
                      The controller handler that:
                        1. Final validation check
                        2. Collects shipping, payment, and cart data
                        3. Sends to the backend (OData or REST)
                        4. Shows success MessageBox
                        5. Clears the cart
                        6. Navigates to an order confirmation page

                    type="Emphasized"
                      Primary action styling.

                    [BEST PRACTICE] After successful order placement:
                      1. Show a success message with order number
                      2. Clear the cart model
                      3. Navigate to a confirmation page (not back to cart)
                      4. Prevent browser back from re-submitting

                    [ADVANCED] PREVENTING DOUBLE SUBMISSIONS
                    Set the button to busy or disabled after first press:
                      oButton.setBusy(true);
                    Then re-enable after the backend responds.
                    -->
                    <Button
                        text="{i18n>placeOrder}"
                        type="Emphasized"
                        icon="sap-icon://accept"
                        press=".onPlaceOrder"
                        class="sapUiMediumMarginTop"
                    />
                </VBox>
            </WizardStep>
        </Wizard>

    </Page>

</mvc:View>
